stopping to smoke. As the coronary risk factors act in a synergistic way, a 
comprehensive approach to the patient is recommended, especially in smokers with 
myocardial infarction. It is justified an intensive intervention because of the 
advantages in this population. The physician should clearly communicate to the 
patient the need of stopping to smoke, which carries sometimes as beneficial 
effects as other interventions. A wise use of replacement therapy with 
transdermal nicotine, together with other useful measures, allows us to manage 
patients with a broad margin of safety, especially in coronary patients, who win 
most benefit from ceasing to smoke.

